}

{
  "action_id": "1710",
  "action_title": "Add sulphur to soil (alongside planting/seeding)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nA randomized, replicated, controlled study in the UK\u00a0found that adding sulphur to soil alongside sowing seeds did not increase heather cover in a majority of cases. One replicated, controlled study in the UK\u00a0found that adding sulphur and spreading heathland clippings had mixed effects on cover of common heather, perennial rye-grass, and common bent. One randomized, controlled study in the UK\u00a0found that adding sulphur to soil alongside planting of heather seedlings increased their survival, though after two years survival was very low."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the most effective interventions for restoring degraded shrubland habitats?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from action documents, several interventions have been studied for restoring degraded shrubland habitats. Planting turf from intact heathland sites has shown positive results, with two randomized, controlled studies in the UK finding that this technique increased the abundance or cover of heathland species and increased seedling abundance for a majority of heathland plant species. Topsoil removal combined with planting or seeding has also demonstrated effectiveness, with replicated, controlled studies showing that this approach increased cover of heathland plants, heather and gorse, while reducing cover of perennial rye-grass. 

For shrubland restoration more broadly, studies have found that restored areas can achieve similar species richness and abundance compared to undisturbed areas for various taxa. A replicated, controlled study in Mexico found that restored shrubland had similar reptile and amphibian species richness but higher lizard abundance compared to unrestored areas. Similarly, site comparison studies in the USA and Mexico found that mammal species richness in restored desert scrub or shrubland was similar to that in undisturbed areas.

However, some interventions showed mixed or limited results. Simple topsoil removal without additional interventions did not consistently increase heather cover or heathland species richness. Spreading clippings of heathland plants showed variable outcomes, with some studies finding increases in heather seedlings but not in other heathland species. Adding sulphur to soil alongside planting or seeding generally did not significantly improve outcomes. A study from the Netherlands found that heathlands restored by topsoil removal had lower butterfly species richness compared to the surrounding landscape, although abundance was higher in areas where heather litter had also been spread.", "action_ids": ["3946", "1703", "1711", "1685", "1701", "1710", "364", "3751", "2569", "1672"]}

